pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Python async function that silently drops exceptions",
    "input": "My FastAPI endpoint sometimes returns None instead of the expected JSON. No errors in logs.",
    "output": "Are you using `asyncio.gather()` or `create_task()` anywhere in that endpoint? And is the function that produces the JSON wrapped in a try/except?\n\n<user>Yes, I use asyncio.gather to fetch from 3 different services in parallel. No try/except around the gather call itself.</user>\n\nThat's the issue. By default, `asyncio.gather()` with `return_exceptions=False` will raise the first exception, but if one of your service functions catches its own exception and returns None, `gather` won't know anything failed.\n\nCheck each service function. I bet one of them has a bare `except` that returns None:\n```python\n# BAD - silently swallows errors\nasync def fetch_user_data(uid):\n    try:\n        resp = await client.get(f\"/users/{uid}\")\n        return resp.json()\n    except Exception:\n        return None  # This is your silent killer\n```\n\nFix: Either let it propagate, or use `return_exceptions=True` and check results:\n```python\nresults = await asyncio.gather(fetch_a(), fetch_b(), fetch_c(), return_exceptions=True)\nfor r in results:\n    if isinstance(r, Exception):\n        logger.error(f\"Service call failed: {r}\")\n        raise HTTPException(500, \"Upstream service failure\")\n```\n\n<user>You nailed it. fetch_inventory had a bare except returning None. But should I use return_exceptions=True or let it crash?</user>\n\nDepends on your failure mode preference:\n\n- **Fail-fast** (let it crash): Don't catch in individual functions, wrap the `gather` in a single try/except. Best when all 3 results are required.\n- **Partial degradation** (`return_exceptions=True`): Best when you can return a useful response even if one service is down.\n\nFor most APIs, fail-fast is safer. Partial results that look complete but aren't cause subtle downstream bugs. Use `return_exceptions=True` only if your response schema explicitly supports optional fields."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Rust lifetime error in a struct that holds a reference",
    "input": "I'm getting `borrowed value does not live long enough` when I try to store a string slice in my struct:\n```rust\nstruct Config<'a> {\n    name: &'a str,\n}\n\nfn load_config() -> Config {\n    let raw = std::fs::read_to_string(\"config.toml\").unwrap();\n    let name = raw.lines().next().unwrap();\n    Config { name }\n}\n```",
    "output": "The problem is clear: `raw` is a `String` owned by `load_config()`. When you take a `&str` slice of it and put it in `Config`, the `String` gets dropped at the end of the function, but `Config` still holds a reference to it.\n\nWhat's your use case for the reference? Is `Config` long-lived (stored in app state) or short-lived (used and discarded)?\n\n<user>It's stored in app state for the entire program lifetime.</user>\n\nThen don't use a reference at all. Own the data:\n```rust\nstruct Config {\n    name: String,\n}\n\nfn load_config() -> Config {\n    let raw = std::fs::read_to_string(\"config.toml\").unwrap();\n    let name = raw.lines().next().unwrap().to_string();\n    Config { name }\n}\n```\n\nThe general rule: if a struct outlives the function that creates it, it must own its data. Use `&'a str` only when the struct is a short-lived view into data owned elsewhere (like a parser token referencing the source text).\n\n<user>But I've seen Cow<'a, str> used for this. Would that help?</user>\n\n`Cow<'a, str>` is useful when your struct *sometimes* borrows and *sometimes* owns \u2014 like a config that has defaults (borrowed `&'static str`) but can be overridden (owned `String`):\n```rust\nuse std::borrow::Cow;\n\nstruct Config<'a> {\n    name: Cow<'a, str>,\n}\n\nimpl Config<'static> {\n    fn default() -> Self {\n        Config { name: Cow::Borrowed(\"default_app\") }\n    }\n}\n\nfn load_config() -> Config<'static> {\n    let raw = std::fs::read_to_string(\"config.toml\").unwrap();\n    let name = raw.lines().next().unwrap().to_string();\n    Config { name: Cow::Owned(name) }\n}\n```\n\nBut for your case where it's always loaded from a file, plain `String` is simpler and correct. Don't reach for `Cow` unless you have the mixed-ownership pattern."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Go goroutine leak causing memory growth",
    "input": "My Go HTTP server's memory keeps growing. After a few hours it's using 2GB+. I suspect goroutine leak but not sure how to confirm.",
    "output": "First, let's confirm it's goroutines. Add the pprof handler if you haven't:\n```go\nimport _ \"net/http/pprof\"\n```\n\nThen check the goroutine count:\n```bash\ncurl http://localhost:6060/debug/pprof/goroutine?debug=1 | head -5\n```\n\nWhat does the goroutine count show? And do you use any channels or `time.After` in your request handlers?\n\n<user>Goroutine count is 47,000. I use channels \u2014 each request spawns a goroutine that writes to a channel, and another goroutine reads from it with a timeout using select and time.After.</user>\n\nThat's your leak. `time.After` creates a timer that isn't garbage collected until it fires, but more importantly \u2014 if your writer goroutine sends to a channel and nobody reads (because the reader timed out and moved on), the writer blocks forever.\n\nShow me your select pattern. I bet it looks like this:\n```go\n// LEAKY PATTERN\nfunc handleRequest(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    ch := make(chan Result)\n    go func() {\n        result := expensiveWork()\n        ch <- result  // blocks forever if timeout fires first\n    }()\n    select {\n    case res := <-ch:\n        json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(res)\n    case <-time.After(5 * time.Second):\n        http.Error(w, \"timeout\", 504)\n    }\n}\n```\n\n<user>That's almost exactly my code. How do I fix it?</user>\n\nTwo changes: use a buffered channel (so the writer never blocks) and use `context.WithTimeout` instead of `time.After`:\n```go\nfunc handleRequest(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(r.Context(), 5*time.Second)\n    defer cancel()\n\n    ch := make(chan Result, 1)  // buffered! writer won't block\n    go func() {\n        result := expensiveWork(ctx)  // pass context so it can abort\n        ch <- result\n    }()\n    select {\n    case res := <-ch:\n        json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(res)\n    case <-ctx.Done():\n        http.Error(w, \"timeout\", 504)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nKey fixes:\n1. **Buffered channel (`make(chan Result, 1)`)** \u2014 if the reader is gone, the writer can still send and exit\n2. **`context.WithTimeout`** \u2014 lets `expensiveWork` check `ctx.Done()` and abort early\n3. **`defer cancel()`** \u2014 cleans up the timer immediately instead of waiting for GC"
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a TypeScript type narrowing issue with discriminated unions",
    "input": "TypeScript says `Property 'data' does not exist on type 'ApiResponse'` even though I'm checking the status:\n```typescript\ntype ApiResponse = \n  | { status: 'ok'; data: Record<string, unknown> }\n  | { status: 'error'; message: string };\n\nfunction handle(resp: ApiResponse) {\n  if (resp.status === 'ok') {\n    console.log(resp.data); // ERROR here\n  }\n}\n```",
    "output": "That code should work \u2014 discriminated unions with literal type checks do narrow correctly in TypeScript. The error suggests something else is going on.\n\nCan you check: is `status` possibly typed as `string` instead of a literal? For example, are you creating the response object like this?\n```typescript\nconst resp = { status: 'ok', data: { id: 1 } };\nhandle(resp);  // status inferred as `string`, not `'ok'`\n```\n\n<user>Oh \u2014 yes, I'm building the object in a variable first and then passing it. That's different from passing inline?</user>\n\nExactly. When you assign to a variable without a type annotation, TypeScript widens `'ok'` to `string`. Two fixes:\n\n**Option 1: `as const`**\n```typescript\nconst resp = { status: 'ok' as const, data: { id: 1 } };\nhandle(resp); // works\n```\n\n**Option 2: Type annotation on the variable**\n```typescript\nconst resp: ApiResponse = { status: 'ok', data: { id: 1 } };\nhandle(resp); // works\n```\n\n**Option 3: `satisfies` (TypeScript 4.9+)**\n```typescript\nconst resp = { status: 'ok', data: { id: 1 } } satisfies ApiResponse;\n// keeps the narrow type AND validates the shape\n```\n\n<user>What's the difference between Option 2 and Option 3?</user>\n\nWith `: ApiResponse`, the variable is typed as the full union \u2014 you lose the knowledge that it's specifically the `ok` variant. With `satisfies`, you keep the narrow inferred type:\n```typescript\nconst resp: ApiResponse = { status: 'ok', data: { id: 1 } };\nresp.data; // ERROR \u2014 TypeScript only knows it's ApiResponse, not which variant\n\nconst resp2 = { status: 'ok', data: { id: 1 } } satisfies ApiResponse;\nresp2.data; // WORKS \u2014 type is { status: 'ok'; data: { id: number } }\n```\n\nUse `satisfies` when you want validation + narrow types. Use `: Type` when you intentionally want to widen."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a C++ segfault in a vector of unique_ptr",
    "input": "Getting a segfault when iterating a `vector<unique_ptr<Node>>` after removing elements. Using erase-remove idiom.",
    "output": "Can you show me your erase-remove code? The classic pitfall with `unique_ptr` containers is accessing moved-from pointers.\n\n<user>Here it is:\n```cpp\nauto it = std::remove_if(nodes.begin(), nodes.end(),\n    [](const std::unique_ptr<Node>& n) { return n->is_expired(); });\nnodes.erase(it, nodes.end());\n// Later...\nfor (auto& n : nodes) {\n    n->update(); // segfault here sometimes\n}\n```</user>\n\nThe erase-remove pattern itself is correct. The segfault must be elsewhere. Key question: is anything else holding raw pointers to the `Node` objects? Or is `is_expired()` or `update()` modifying the vector (adding/removing elements)?\n\n<user>Yes, nodes hold raw pointers to their parent nodes which are also in the vector. And update() can mark other nodes as expired and remove them.</user>\n\nThere are two bugs:\n\n**Bug 1: Dangling parent pointers.** When you erase expired nodes, any surviving node whose parent was expired now holds a dangling raw pointer. Dereferencing it in `update()` is the segfault.\n\n**Bug 2: Mutating the vector during iteration.** If `update()` removes elements from `nodes`, the range-for loop has undefined behavior.\n\nFixes:\n```cpp\n// Fix Bug 1: Null out parent pointers before erasing\nauto it = std::remove_if(nodes.begin(), nodes.end(),\n    [](const std::unique_ptr<Node>& n) { return n->is_expired(); });\n\n// Collect addresses being removed\nstd::unordered_set<Node*> dying;\nfor (auto dead = it; dead != nodes.end(); ++dead)\n    dying.insert(dead->get());\n\n// Clear dangling references\nfor (auto& n : nodes)\n    if (n->parent && dying.count(n->parent))\n        n->parent = nullptr;\n\nnodes.erase(it, nodes.end());\n\n// Fix Bug 2: Collect updates, apply after iteration\nfor (auto& n : nodes)\n    n->update();  // update() must NOT modify the vector\n// Process removals in a separate pass\n```\n\nLong-term, consider replacing raw parent pointers with indices or `std::weak_ptr` (requires `shared_ptr` instead of `unique_ptr`)."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug Python pandas DataFrame merge producing duplicate rows",
    "input": "My DataFrame merge is producing way more rows than expected. Left df has 10k rows, right has 5k, result has 80k. I'm using inner merge on 'user_id'.",
    "output": "The multiplied row count means you have duplicate `user_id` values in one or both DataFrames. A merge does a cross product within each matching key \u2014 if user_id 42 appears 3 times on the left and 4 times on the right, you get 12 rows for that user.\n\nCheck for duplicates:\n```python\nprint(f\"Left dupes: {left_df['user_id'].duplicated().sum()}\")\nprint(f\"Right dupes: {right_df['user_id'].duplicated().sum()}\")\n```\n\nWhat's the output?\n\n<user>Left has 0 duplicates, right has 4,200 duplicates out of 5,000 rows. It's a transactions table \u2014 multiple transactions per user.</user>\n\nThat's expected for a transactions table. The question is: what do you actually want?\n\n1. **One row per user with their latest transaction**: aggregate first, then merge\n2. **One row per user with transaction count/sum**: group first, then merge\n3. **All user-transaction combinations**: your current merge is correct, 80k is expected\n\nWhich one?\n\n<user>I want each user with their total transaction amount and count.</user>\n\nAggregate first, then merge:\n```python\ntxn_summary = right_df.groupby('user_id').agg(\n    txn_count=('amount', 'size'),\n    total_amount=('amount', 'sum'),\n    last_txn_date=('date', 'max')\n).reset_index()\n\nresult = left_df.merge(txn_summary, on='user_id', how='left')\nprint(result.shape)  # Should be (10000, ...)\n```\n\nThis gives you exactly 10k rows \u2014 one per user \u2014 with aggregated transaction data. Users with no transactions get NaN in the transaction columns (due to `how='left'`)."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Rust borrow checker error with mutable and immutable references",
    "input": "I'm getting `cannot borrow as mutable because it is also borrowed as immutable`:\n```rust\nlet mut map: HashMap<String, Vec<i32>> = HashMap::new();\nfor key in map.keys() {\n    if map[key].is_empty() {\n        map.remove(key);\n    }\n}\n```",
    "output": "Classic borrow conflict. `map.keys()` borrows `map` immutably for the iterator's lifetime. Then `map.remove()` tries to borrow it mutably while the iterator is still alive.\n\nDo you need to remove entries based on a condition? Or is there more complex logic in the loop?\n\n<user>Just removing entries where the vec is empty. Could be thousands of entries so I need it efficient.</user>\n\nUse `retain` \u2014 it was designed for exactly this:\n```rust\nmap.retain(|_key, value| !value.is_empty());\n```\n\nOne line, no borrow issues, O(n). `retain` gives you mutable access to each entry and removes those where the closure returns `false`.\n\n<user>What if I also need to move the non-empty values into a different structure while removing them?</user>\n\nThen use `drain` or `extract_if` (nightly). On stable, collect keys first to break the borrow:\n```rust\nlet empty_keys: Vec<String> = map.iter()\n    .filter(|(_, v)| v.is_empty())\n    .map(|(k, _)| k.clone())\n    .collect();\n\nfor key in &empty_keys {\n    map.remove(key);\n}\n\n// Or to split into two maps:\nlet (empty, full): (HashMap<_, _>, HashMap<_, _>) = map.into_iter()\n    .partition(|(_, v)| v.is_empty());\n```\n\nThe `into_iter()` + `partition` approach consumes the original map, so no borrow conflicts at all. Use this when you're restructuring the whole collection."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Go interface nil comparison that fails unexpectedly",
    "input": "My Go error check is broken. I return nil from a function but `err != nil` is true:\n```go\nfunc doWork() error {\n    var err *MyError = nil\n    return err\n}\n\nif err := doWork(); err != nil {\n    fmt.Println(\"error!\", err)  // This prints!\n}\n```",
    "output": "This is Go's most notorious gotcha: a nil pointer wrapped in an interface is not a nil interface.\n\nWhen you return `err` (typed `*MyError`), Go wraps it in the `error` interface as `(type=*MyError, value=nil)`. An interface is only nil when BOTH type and value are nil: `(type=nil, value=nil)`.\n\nSince the interface carries type information, `err != nil` is `true` even though the underlying pointer is nil.\n\n<user>How do I fix it? I need to return nil sometimes and *MyError other times.</user>\n\nTwo options:\n\n**Option 1 (preferred): Return `error` interface directly**\n```go\nfunc doWork() error {\n    if somethingFailed {\n        return &MyError{msg: \"failed\"}\n    }\n    return nil  // This is a true nil interface\n}\n```\nNever assign to a typed nil variable and then return it.\n\n**Option 2: Check in the function before returning**\n```go\nfunc doWork() error {\n    var err *MyError\n    // ... work that might set err ...\n    if err == nil {\n        return nil  // Return untyped nil\n    }\n    return err\n}\n```\n\n<user>Is there a way to detect this mistake with a linter?</user>\n\nYes. Use `nilness` from `go vet` and `nilerr` from golangci-lint:\n```bash\ngolangci-lint run --enable nilerr,govet\n```\n\nAlso, `staticcheck` (SA4023) catches exactly this pattern \u2014 returning a typed nil as an interface. Add it to your CI pipeline and you'll never hit this again."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a JavaScript memory leak in a React component with event listeners",
    "input": "My React app slows down over time. Chrome DevTools shows detached DOM nodes piling up. I think it's related to my modal component.",
    "output": "Detached DOM nodes usually mean event listeners or closures are holding references to unmounted components. Does your modal component add any `window` or `document` level event listeners? And how are you mounting/unmounting it?\n\n<user>It adds a keydown listener for Escape key to close the modal:\n```jsx\nfunction Modal({ onClose }) {\n  useEffect(() => {\n    document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {\n      if (e.key === 'Escape') onClose();\n    });\n  }, []);\n  return <div className=\"modal\">...</div>;\n}\n```</user>\n\nTwo problems:\n\n1. **No cleanup function** \u2014 the event listener is never removed when the modal unmounts\n2. **Stale closure** \u2014 `onClose` is captured from the first render and never updates (empty deps array)\n\nFixed:\n```jsx\nfunction Modal({ onClose }) {\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const handler = (e) => {\n      if (e.key === 'Escape') onClose();\n    };\n    document.addEventListener('keydown', handler);\n    return () => document.removeEventListener('keydown', handler);\n  }, [onClose]);\n  return <div className=\"modal\">...</div>;\n}\n```\n\nKey changes:\n- **Return a cleanup function** that removes the listener\n- **Include `onClose` in deps** so the handler updates if the callback changes\n- **Named function** so `removeEventListener` can find and remove the exact listener\n\n<user>I have like 20 components that might have similar issues. How do I find them all?</user>\n\nSearch your codebase:\n```bash\ngrep -rn 'addEventListener' src/ --include='*.tsx' --include='*.jsx'\n```\n\nEvery `addEventListener` should have a matching `removeEventListener` in a useEffect cleanup. Also ensure the `react-hooks/exhaustive-deps` ESLint rule is enabled \u2014 it catches missing cleanup dependencies. For the DevTools approach: take a heap snapshot, open/close the modal 10 times, take another snapshot, and compare \u2014 you'll see exactly which DOM nodes are retained."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Python process that hangs on multiprocessing.Pool",
    "input": "My script freezes after calling pool.map(). No error, just hangs. It worked fine with small inputs but hangs on larger datasets (~50k items).",
    "output": "A few common causes for `Pool.map` hanging on large inputs:\n1. A worker raises an exception that can't be pickled\n2. Data being sent/returned exceeds pipe buffer limits\n3. Workers deadlock on a shared resource\n\nWhat does your worker function do? Does it return large objects or use any shared state (files, databases, locks)?\n\n<user>Each worker processes a text file and returns a dictionary with the results. The dict can be a few MB. No shared state.\n```python\ndef process_file(path):\n    with open(path) as f:\n        data = f.read()\n    return {'path': path, 'stats': analyze(data), 'content': data}\n```</user>\n\nReturning the full file content in `'content'` is your problem. With 50k files, you're sending gigabytes back through the multiprocessing pipe. The pipe buffer fills up, workers block on write, and the parent blocks waiting for workers \u2014 deadlock.\n\nFix: don't return large data through the pool. Write results to disk in the worker:\n```python\ndef process_file(path):\n    with open(path) as f:\n        data = f.read()\n    stats = analyze(data)\n    out_path = path + '.result.json'\n    with open(out_path, 'w') as f:\n        json.dump({'stats': stats, 'content': data}, f)\n    return {'path': path, 'out_path': out_path, 'stats': stats}\n```\n\nOr use `pool.imap_unordered` with a smaller chunksize to process incrementally:\n```python\nresults = []\nfor result in pool.imap_unordered(process_file, paths, chunksize=100):\n    results.append(result)\n```\n\n<user>Switching to imap_unordered helped but it's still slow. Is there a faster approach for file processing?</user>\n\nFor I/O-bound work like reading files, use `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` instead \u2014 no pickling overhead, no IPC pipes:\n```python\nfrom concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor, as_completed\n\nwith ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=16) as executor:\n    futures = {executor.submit(process_file, p): p for p in paths}\n    for future in as_completed(futures):\n        result = future.result()\n```\n\nThreads share memory so returning large dicts is free. Use multiprocessing only for CPU-bound work where you need to bypass the GIL."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a C++ template SFINAE issue with error messages",
    "input": "I'm trying to write a function that only works for integral types but I'm getting a wall of template errors:\n```cpp\ntemplate<typename T>\nauto to_hex(T value) -> std::enable_if_t<std::is_integral_v<T>, std::string> {\n    std::ostringstream ss;\n    ss << std::hex << value;\n    return ss.str();\n}\n\nto_hex(3.14); // Expected clean error, got 50 lines of template noise\n```",
    "output": "The SFINAE is correct \u2014 `to_hex(3.14)` should fail substitution and give a \"no matching function\" error. If you're getting 50 lines of template noise, you might have another overload or something else going on.\n\nWhat compiler and version? And can you paste just the first 3-4 lines of the error?\n\n<user>GCC 11. Error says:\n```\nerror: no matching function for call to 'to_hex(double)'\nnote: candidate: template<class T> std::enable_if_t<is_integral_v<T>, string> to_hex(T)\nnote: template argument deduction/substitution failed:\n```\nActually, that's only 3 lines. My real problem is I want a helpful error message, not just \"no match\".</user>\n\nGot it. For better errors, use `static_assert` with `if constexpr` (C++17) or concepts (C++20):\n\n**C++17:**\n```cpp\ntemplate<typename T>\nstd::string to_hex(T value) {\n    static_assert(std::is_integral_v<T>, \"to_hex() requires an integral type\");\n    std::ostringstream ss;\n    ss << std::hex << value;\n    return ss.str();\n}\n// Error: static assertion failed: to_hex() requires an integral type\n```\n\n**C++20 \u2014 concepts:**\n```cpp\ntemplate<std::integral T>\nstd::string to_hex(T value) {\n    std::ostringstream ss;\n    ss << std::hex << value;\n    return ss.str();\n}\n// Error: constraints not satisfied [with T = double]\n```\n\n<user>We're on C++17. Is static_assert better than SFINAE here?</user>\n\nIt depends on whether you need overload resolution:\n\n- **`static_assert`**: Use when there's only ONE version of the function. Gives a clear error message. But it's a hard error \u2014 it prevents other overloads from being considered.\n- **SFINAE / `enable_if`**: Use when you have MULTIPLE overloads and want the compiler to pick the right one.\n\nFor your `to_hex` case with no overloads, `static_assert` is strictly better \u2014 clearer intent, better errors, simpler code."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Python import cycle causing AttributeError",
    "input": "I get `AttributeError: partially initialized module 'models' has no attribute 'User'` when starting my Flask app. All my imports look correct.",
    "output": "This is a circular import. Module A imports module B which imports module A \u2014 but A hasn't finished loading yet, so its attributes don't exist.\n\nWhat does your import structure look like? Specifically, what imports what between your models, routes, and app modules?\n\n<user>I have:\n- app.py imports from routes.py\n- routes.py imports User from models.py\n- models.py imports db from app.py (for SQLAlchemy)\n</user>\n\nClassic Flask circular import: `app.py -> routes.py -> models.py -> app.py` (cycle).\n\nThe standard fix is to break the cycle with a separate extensions module:\n```python\n# extensions.py (NEW \u2014 no imports from your own code)\nfrom flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy\ndb = SQLAlchemy()\n\n# models.py\nfrom extensions import db  # Not from app!\nclass User(db.Model):\n    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)\n\n# app.py\nfrom flask import Flask\nfrom extensions import db\n\ndef create_app():\n    app = Flask(__name__)\n    db.init_app(app)\n    from routes import bp  # Import inside function, after app exists\n    app.register_blueprint(bp)\n    return app\n```\n\n<user>I already have a lot of code doing `from app import db`. Is there a way to fix it without changing every import?</user>\n\nYes \u2014 keep `db` importable from `app.py` as a re-export:\n```python\n# extensions.py\nfrom flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy\ndb = SQLAlchemy()\n\n# app.py\nfrom extensions import db  # Create the binding\n# Now `from app import db` still works because app re-exports it\n```\n\nNo other files need to change. The key insight: `db` must be *created* in a module that doesn't import your application code. `app.py` can re-export it, but can't be where it's defined."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Go HTTP handler that returns empty body intermittently",
    "input": "My Go API sometimes returns 200 with an empty body. It's not consistent \u2014 same request works sometimes, fails others. Using `json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(data)`.",
    "output": "Intermittent empty responses usually mean a panic is being recovered somewhere, or middleware is writing headers prematurely.\n\nDo you have any middleware \u2014 logging, auth, CORS? And is there a `recover` middleware?\n\n<user>Yes, I have a recover middleware:\n```go\nfunc recoverMiddleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {\n    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        defer func() {\n            if err := recover(); err != nil {\n                w.WriteHeader(200) // Don't expose errors\n            }\n        }()\n        next.ServeHTTP(w, r)\n    })\n}\n```</user>\n\nFound it. Your recover middleware catches panics and writes a 200 with empty body \u2014 silently swallowing the error. The intermittent nature means your handler panics sometimes (likely a nil pointer dereference on optional data).\n\nFix the middleware:\n```go\nfunc recoverMiddleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {\n    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        defer func() {\n            if err := recover(); err != nil {\n                log.Printf(\"PANIC: %v\\n%s\", err, debug.Stack())\n                w.WriteHeader(http.StatusInternalServerError)\n                json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(map[string]string{\n                    \"error\": \"internal server error\",\n                })\n            }\n        }()\n        next.ServeHTTP(w, r)\n    })\n}\n```\n\nThen check your logs for the panic stack trace \u2014 that'll point to the real bug.\n\n<user>Changed it, now I see: `PANIC: runtime error: invalid memory address or nil pointer dereference` in the handler that loads user preferences. Some users don't have preferences set.</user>\n\nNil pointer on optional data \u2014 exactly as suspected. Check before accessing:\n```go\nfunc getPreferences(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    user := getUser(r.Context())\n    prefs := user.Preferences // This is *Preferences, can be nil\n    \n    if prefs == nil {\n        prefs = &DefaultPreferences  // Use defaults\n    }\n    json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(prefs)\n}\n```\n\nAlso: never return 200 in a recover handler. A recovered panic is always a 500 \u2014 hiding it makes bugs invisible."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Rust async runtime conflict between tokio and actix",
    "input": "My Rust web app panics with `there is no reactor running` when I call a tokio function inside an actix-web handler.",
    "output": "Actix-web uses its own async runtime (actix-rt), which is built on tokio but with a different configuration. If you're using a library that calls `tokio::spawn` or `tokio::runtime::Handle::current()` directly, it might not find the expected tokio runtime.\n\nWhat library is throwing the error? And what version of actix-web?\n\n<user>I'm using `sqlx` with the tokio runtime feature. actix-web 4.\n```rust\n#[actix_web::main]\nasync fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {\n    let pool = sqlx::PgPool::connect(\"postgres://...\").await.unwrap();\n    HttpServer::new(move || {\n        App::new().app_data(web::Data::new(pool.clone()))\n    }).bind(\"0.0.0.0:8080\")?.run().await\n}\n```</user>\n\nActix-web 4 uses tokio under the hood, so this should work. The issue is likely in your `Cargo.toml` \u2014 you might have conflicting tokio versions.\n\nCheck:\n```bash\ncargo tree -i tokio\n```\n\nDo you see multiple tokio versions?\n\n<user>cargo tree shows tokio 1.34 and tokio 1.32. sqlx has `runtime-tokio-rustls` feature.</user>\n\nMultiple tokio versions \u2014 that's the bug. sqlx is using tokio 1.32 while actix-web uses 1.34. They're different instances of the runtime, so sqlx can't find actix's reactor.\n\nFix by ensuring one version in `Cargo.toml`:\n```toml\n[dependencies]\ntokio = { version = \"1.34\", features = [\"full\"] }\nsqlx = { version = \"0.7\", features = [\"runtime-tokio-rustls\", \"postgres\"] }\n```\n\nRun `cargo update` to resolve the tree. Then verify:\n```bash\ncargo tree -i tokio | grep tokio\n# Should show only one version\n```\n\nThe root cause: Cargo treats `tokio 1.32` and `tokio 1.34` as compatible but keeps both if different deps request them with incompatible feature sets. Explicitly depending on the newer version usually unifies them."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Debug a Python FastAPI app returning 422 for valid-looking requests",
    "input": "My FastAPI endpoint returns 422 Unprocessable Entity even though my JSON looks correct:\n```python\n@app.post(\"/items\")\nasync def create_item(name: str, price: float):\n    return {\"name\": name, \"price\": price}\n```\nI'm sending: `{\"name\": \"widget\", \"price\": 9.99}`",
    "output": "The issue is how FastAPI interprets the parameters. When you write `name: str, price: float` as plain function arguments (not a Pydantic model), FastAPI treats them as **query parameters**, not body fields.\n\nSo it's looking for `?name=widget&price=9.99` in the URL, and ignoring your JSON body.\n\n<user>Oh! So I need to use a Pydantic model for JSON body?</user>\n\nYes. Two options:\n\n**Option 1: Pydantic model (recommended)**\n```python\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n\nclass ItemCreate(BaseModel):\n    name: str\n    price: float\n\n@app.post(\"/items\")\nasync def create_item(item: ItemCreate):\n    return {\"name\": item.name, \"price\": item.price}\n```\n\n**Option 2: `Body()` annotation (for simple cases)**\n```python\nfrom fastapi import Body\n\n@app.post(\"/items\")\nasync def create_item(name: str = Body(), price: float = Body()):\n    return {\"name\": name, \"price\": price}\n```\n\n<user>What if I want some params from the URL path, some from query, and some from body?</user>\n\nFastAPI decides based on how you declare them:\n```python\n@app.post(\"/items/{category}\")\nasync def create_item(\n    category: str,                    # Path param (in URL path)\n    urgent: bool = False,             # Query param (has default)\n    item: ItemCreate = Body(),        # Body (Pydantic model or Body())\n):\n    return {\"category\": category, \"urgent\": urgent, **item.dict()}\n```\n\nRules:\n- **In the path** (`{category}`) -> path parameter\n- **Plain type with default** -> query parameter\n- **Pydantic model** -> body\n- **Annotated with `Body()`** -> body\n- **Plain type without default and not in path** -> query parameter (this is the gotcha you hit)"
})

