pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a Python retry decorator implementation",
    "input": "Please review my retry decorator:\n```python\nimport time\nimport functools\n\ndef retry(max_retries=3, delay=1):\n    def decorator(func):\n        @functools.wraps(func)\n        def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n            for attempt in range(max_retries):\n                try:\n                    return func(*args, **kwargs)\n                except Exception:\n                    if attempt == max_retries - 1:\n                        raise\n                    time.sleep(delay)\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n```",
    "output": "Functional but has several issues:\n\n1. **Catches all exceptions** \u2014 you'll retry on `KeyboardInterrupt`, `SystemExit`, `TypeError`, etc. Only retry on transient failures.\n2. **Fixed delay** \u2014 no exponential backoff, so you'll hammer a failing service.\n3. **No logging** \u2014 retries are silent, making debugging impossible.\n4. **No jitter** \u2014 if 100 clients retry simultaneously with the same delay, they'll all hit together.\n\nImproved version:\n```python\nimport time, functools, logging, random\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\ndef retry(max_retries=3, delay=1, backoff=2, exceptions=(IOError, OSError)):\n    def decorator(func):\n        @functools.wraps(func)\n        def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n            current_delay = delay\n            for attempt in range(max_retries):\n                try:\n                    return func(*args, **kwargs)\n                except exceptions as e:\n                    if attempt == max_retries - 1:\n                        raise\n                    jitter = random.uniform(0, current_delay * 0.1)\n                    logger.warning(f\"{func.__name__} attempt {attempt+1} failed: {e}, retrying in {current_delay:.1f}s\")\n                    time.sleep(current_delay + jitter)\n                    current_delay *= backoff\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n```\n\n<user>Good points. But what about async functions? This would block the event loop.</user>\n\nRight \u2014 you need a dual version. Detect if the wrapped function is async:\n```python\nimport asyncio, inspect\n\ndef retry(max_retries=3, delay=1, backoff=2, exceptions=(IOError, OSError)):\n    def decorator(func):\n        if inspect.iscoroutinefunction(func):\n            @functools.wraps(func)\n            async def async_wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n                current_delay = delay\n                for attempt in range(max_retries):\n                    try:\n                        return await func(*args, **kwargs)\n                    except exceptions as e:\n                        if attempt == max_retries - 1:\n                            raise\n                        await asyncio.sleep(current_delay)\n                        current_delay *= backoff\n            return async_wrapper\n        else:\n            @functools.wraps(func)\n            def sync_wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n                # ... same as before with time.sleep\n                pass\n            return sync_wrapper\n    return decorator\n```\n\n<user>Should I use the tenacity library instead of rolling my own?</user>\n\nFor production code, yes. `tenacity` handles all edge cases:\n```python\nfrom tenacity import retry, stop_after_attempt, wait_exponential, retry_if_exception_type\n\n@retry(\n    stop=stop_after_attempt(3),\n    wait=wait_exponential(multiplier=1, max=10),\n    retry=retry_if_exception_type((IOError, ConnectionError)),\n)\nasync def fetch_data():\n    ...\n```\n\nIt handles async natively, has circuit breakers, custom callbacks, and is battle-tested. Roll your own only if you need zero dependencies."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a TypeScript API client class",
    "input": "Review my API client:\n```typescript\nclass ApiClient {\n  private baseUrl: string;\n  private token: string;\n\n  constructor(baseUrl: string, token: string) {\n    this.baseUrl = baseUrl;\n    this.token = token;\n  }\n\n  async get(path: string): Promise<any> {\n    const resp = await fetch(`${this.baseUrl}${path}`, {\n      headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` }\n    });\n    return resp.json();\n  }\n\n  async post(path: string, body: any): Promise<any> {\n    const resp = await fetch(`${this.baseUrl}${path}`, {\n      method: 'POST',\n      headers: {\n        Authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}`,\n        'Content-Type': 'application/json'\n      },\n      body: JSON.stringify(body)\n    });\n    return resp.json();\n  }\n}\n```",
    "output": "Several issues:\n\n1. **No error handling** \u2014 `fetch` doesn't throw on 4xx/5xx. A 404 returns successfully, and you try to parse error HTML as JSON.\n2. **`any` everywhere** \u2014 defeats the purpose of TypeScript. Use generics.\n3. **No timeout** \u2014 a hanging request blocks forever.\n4. **Token is immutable** \u2014 can't refresh expired tokens.\n\nTighter version:\n```typescript\nclass ApiError extends Error {\n  constructor(public status: number, public body: unknown) {\n    super(`API error ${status}`);\n  }\n}\n\nclass ApiClient {\n  constructor(\n    private baseUrl: string,\n    private getToken: () => string | Promise<string>,\n    private timeout = 30_000\n  ) {}\n\n  async get<T>(path: string): Promise<T> {\n    return this.request<T>('GET', path);\n  }\n\n  async post<T>(path: string, body: unknown): Promise<T> {\n    return this.request<T>('POST', path, body);\n  }\n\n  private async request<T>(method: string, path: string, body?: unknown): Promise<T> {\n    const token = await this.getToken();\n    const controller = new AbortController();\n    const timer = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), this.timeout);\n\n    try {\n      const resp = await fetch(`${this.baseUrl}${path}`, {\n        method,\n        headers: {\n          Authorization: `Bearer ${token}`,\n          ...(body ? { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n        },\n        body: body ? JSON.stringify(body) : undefined,\n        signal: controller.signal,\n      });\n      if (!resp.ok) throw new ApiError(resp.status, await resp.json().catch(() => null));\n      return resp.json() as Promise<T>;\n    } finally {\n      clearTimeout(timer);\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n<user>Why a `getToken` function instead of a string? Seems over-engineered.</user>\n\nIt handles token refresh without the client knowing about auth logic:\n```typescript\n// Simple case:\nconst client = new ApiClient('https://api.example.com', () => 'static-token');\n\n// Refresh case:\nconst client = new ApiClient('https://api.example.com', () => {\n  if (tokenExpired()) return refreshToken();\n  return currentToken;\n});\n```\n\nThe caller controls auth strategy. The API client doesn't need to know about OAuth, API keys, or session tokens. One function parameter covers all cases."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a Go database connection pool wrapper",
    "input": "Please review:\n```go\ntype DB struct {\n\tpool *sql.DB\n}\n\nfunc NewDB(dsn string) *DB {\n\tpool, err := sql.Open(\"postgres\", dsn)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t}\n\treturn &DB{pool: pool}\n}\n\nfunc (db *DB) GetUser(id int) (*User, error) {\n\tvar u User\n\terr := db.pool.QueryRow(\"SELECT id, name, email FROM users WHERE id = \" + strconv.Itoa(id)).Scan(&u.ID, &u.Name, &u.Email)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\treturn &u, nil\n}\n```",
    "output": "Three significant issues:\n\n**1. SQL injection** \u2014 you're concatenating the id directly into the query. Even though it's an int today, this pattern spreads to string fields:\n```go\n// BAD\n\"SELECT ... WHERE id = \" + strconv.Itoa(id)\n// GOOD\n\"SELECT ... WHERE id = $1\", id\n```\n\n**2. `sql.Open` doesn't connect** \u2014 it only validates the DSN. Your app starts \"successfully\" with a dead database and fails on the first query. Add a Ping:\n```go\nfunc NewDB(dsn string) (*DB, error) {\n\tpool, err := sql.Open(\"postgres\", dsn)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"open db: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\tif err := pool.Ping(); err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"ping db: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\tpool.SetMaxOpenConns(25)\n\tpool.SetMaxIdleConns(5)\n\tpool.SetConnMaxLifetime(5 * time.Minute)\n\treturn &DB{pool: pool}, nil\n}\n```\n\n**3. `log.Fatal` in a library function** \u2014 kills the entire process. Return errors and let the caller decide.\n\n<user>Good catches. For the SQL injection point \u2014 we only have int IDs so it's safe. Is parameterized query actually necessary here?</user>\n\nYes, for three reasons:\n\n1. **Habits spread.** The next developer copies your pattern for a string field.\n2. **Prepared statement caching.** Parameterized queries get cached by PostgreSQL. String concatenation creates a new plan every time.\n3. **Zero cost.** `db.pool.QueryRow(\"SELECT ... WHERE id = $1\", id)` is the same amount of code.\n\nThere's no scenario where string concatenation is better.\n\n<user>Should I use sqlx or stick with database/sql?</user>\n\n`sqlx` is worth it. Key wins:\n```go\n// database/sql \u2014 manual column mapping\nvar u User\nerr := row.Scan(&u.ID, &u.Name, &u.Email)  // Order must match query!\n\n// sqlx \u2014 struct scanning\nvar u User\nerr := db.GetContext(ctx, &u, \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1\", id)\n```\n\nWith `database/sql`, adding a column means updating every `Scan()` call. With `sqlx`, struct tags handle it. It's a thin wrapper with no ORM magic \u2014 just less boilerplate."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a Rust error handling implementation",
    "input": "Review my error enum:\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nenum AppError {\n    NotFound,\n    DatabaseError(String),\n    ValidationError(String),\n    InternalError(String),\n}\n\nimpl std::fmt::Display for AppError {\n    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut std::fmt::Formatter) -> std::fmt::Result {\n        match self {\n            AppError::NotFound => write!(f, \"Not found\"),\n            AppError::DatabaseError(e) => write!(f, \"Database error: {}\", e),\n            AppError::ValidationError(e) => write!(f, \"Validation error: {}\", e),\n            AppError::InternalError(e) => write!(f, \"Internal error: {}\", e),\n        }\n    }\n}\n\nimpl std::error::Error for AppError {}\n```",
    "output": "Solid foundation, but missing key functionality:\n\n1. **No `From` implementations** \u2014 you can't use `?` to convert from `sqlx::Error`, `serde_json::Error`, etc.\n2. **Strings lose the original error** \u2014 `DatabaseError(String)` discards the original error's type, backtrace, and source chain.\n3. **No HTTP status mapping** (if this is a web app).\n\nImproved:\n```rust\nuse thiserror::Error;\n\n#[derive(Debug, Error)]\npub enum AppError {\n    #[error(\"resource not found\")]\n    NotFound,\n\n    #[error(\"database error\")]\n    Database(#[from] sqlx::Error),\n\n    #[error(\"validation: {0}\")]\n    Validation(String),\n\n    #[error(\"internal error\")]\n    Internal(#[from] anyhow::Error),\n}\n```\n\n`thiserror` derives `Display`, `Error`, and `From` impls automatically.\n\n<user>I've seen people use anyhow vs thiserror. When do I use which?</user>\n\nSimple rule:\n\n- **`thiserror`** \u2014 for libraries and public APIs. Creates typed errors that callers can match on.\n- **`anyhow`** \u2014 for applications (binaries). When you don't need callers to match on specific errors, just propagate context.\n\nMany apps use both:\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Error)]\npub enum AppError {\n    #[error(\"not found\")]\n    NotFound,\n    #[error(\"unauthorized\")]\n    Unauthorized,\n    #[error(transparent)]\n    Other(#[from] anyhow::Error),\n}\n```\n\n<user>How would I map these to HTTP status codes in actix-web?</user>\n\nImplement `ResponseError`:\n```rust\nimpl actix_web::ResponseError for AppError {\n    fn status_code(&self) -> StatusCode {\n        match self {\n            AppError::NotFound => StatusCode::NOT_FOUND,\n            AppError::Unauthorized => StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED,\n            AppError::Validation(_) => StatusCode::BAD_REQUEST,\n            AppError::Database(_) | AppError::Other(_) => StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow handlers can return `Result<HttpResponse, AppError>` and errors automatically become proper HTTP responses. Never expose internal error details to clients \u2014 log them server-side, return a generic message."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a Python data pipeline class",
    "input": "Review this ETL pipeline:\n```python\nclass Pipeline:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.steps = []\n    \n    def add_step(self, func):\n        self.steps.append(func)\n        return self\n    \n    def run(self, data):\n        result = data\n        for step in self.steps:\n            result = step(result)\n        return result\n\n# Usage\np = Pipeline()\np.add_step(lambda df: df.dropna())\np.add_step(lambda df: df[df['age'] > 18])\np.add_step(lambda df: df.assign(name=df['name'].str.upper()))\nresult = p.run(raw_df)\n```",
    "output": "The pattern is clean but fragile for production ETL:\n\n1. **No error context** \u2014 if step 7 of 12 fails, you get a traceback inside a lambda with no indication of which step it was.\n2. **No intermediate checkpoints** \u2014 a failure at step 11 means re-running all 10 previous steps.\n3. **Lambdas are un-inspectable** \u2014 `repr(step)` gives `<lambda>`, making debugging impossible.\n\nMinimal improvement:\n```python\nclass Pipeline:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.steps: list[tuple[str, Callable]] = []\n    \n    def add_step(self, name: str, func: Callable):\n        self.steps.append((name, func))\n        return self\n    \n    def run(self, data, checkpoint_dir: str | None = None):\n        result = data\n        for i, (name, step) in enumerate(self.steps):\n            try:\n                result = step(result)\n                logger.info(f\"Step {i+1}/{len(self.steps)} '{name}': {len(result)} rows\")\n                if checkpoint_dir:\n                    result.to_parquet(f\"{checkpoint_dir}/step_{i}_{name}.parquet\")\n            except Exception as e:\n                raise RuntimeError(f\"Pipeline failed at step {i+1} '{name}'\") from e\n        return result\n```\n\n<user>I like the named steps. But checkpointing every step to parquet seems expensive for a 12-step pipeline on 10M rows.</user>\n\nFair point. Make checkpointing selective or checkpoint only on failure:\n```python\nexcept Exception as e:\n    if checkpoint_dir:\n        result.to_parquet(f\"{checkpoint_dir}/failed_before_{name}.parquet\")\n    raise RuntimeError(f\"Failed at '{name}'. Last good state saved.\") from e\n```\n\n<user>Should I look at something like Prefect or Dagster instead?</user>\n\nDepends on your operational needs:\n\n- **This custom Pipeline**: Good for batch scripts, notebooks, single-machine jobs. Zero dependencies.\n- **Prefect/Dagster**: Worth it when you need scheduling, retries, monitoring dashboards, or DAGs with fan-out/fan-in.\n\nIf you're running this in a cron job and it processes in under an hour, the custom pipeline is fine. If you're running multiple schedules with alerting needs, reach for Prefect (lighter) or Dagster (more opinionated)."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a C++ smart pointer usage pattern in a game engine",
    "input": "Review how I'm using smart pointers:\n```cpp\nclass Entity {\npublic:\n    void addChild(std::shared_ptr<Entity> child) {\n        child->parent = shared_from_this();\n        children.push_back(child);\n    }\n    std::shared_ptr<Entity> getParent() { return parent; }\nprivate:\n    std::shared_ptr<Entity> parent;\n    std::vector<std::shared_ptr<Entity>> children;\n};\n```",
    "output": "This has a **circular reference memory leak**. Parent holds `shared_ptr` to children, children hold `shared_ptr` to parent. Neither reference count ever reaches zero.\n\nFix: parent should be `weak_ptr`:\n```cpp\nclass Entity : public std::enable_shared_from_this<Entity> {\npublic:\n    void addChild(std::shared_ptr<Entity> child) {\n        child->parent_ = shared_from_this();\n        children_.push_back(std::move(child));\n    }\n    std::shared_ptr<Entity> getParent() {\n        return parent_.lock();  // Returns nullptr if parent was destroyed\n    }\nprivate:\n    std::weak_ptr<Entity> parent_;\n    std::vector<std::shared_ptr<Entity>> children_;\n};\n```\n\nOwnership flows downward: parent owns children (`shared_ptr`). Children reference parent without ownership (`weak_ptr`).\n\n<user>Makes sense. But for a game engine, is shared_ptr too slow? I've heard raw pointers are faster.</user>\n\nIn hot paths, `shared_ptr` has real overhead: atomic reference count operations (~10-50ns each), plus cache misses on the control block.\n\nFor a game engine, consider `unique_ptr` for ownership + raw pointers for non-owning references:\n```cpp\nclass Entity {\npublic:\n    void addChild(std::unique_ptr<Entity> child) {\n        child->parent_ = this;  // Raw pointer, non-owning\n        children_.push_back(std::move(child));\n    }\nprivate:\n    Entity* parent_ = nullptr;\n    std::vector<std::unique_ptr<Entity>> children_;\n};\n```\n\nThis is safe because the parent always outlives its children.\n\n<user>What about ECS (Entity Component System)? Would that be better for a game engine?</user>\n\nFor performance-critical games, yes. ECS eliminates pointer chasing entirely. Components are stored in contiguous arrays:\n```cpp\nstruct Transform { float x, y, z; };\nstruct Velocity { float dx, dy, dz; };\n\nvoid physics_system(Registry& reg) {\n    for (auto [entity, transform, vel] : reg.view<Transform, Velocity>()) {\n        transform.x += vel.dx * dt;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIterating over 10k entities hits L1 cache the whole way. Libraries: `entt` (C++, header-only, excellent) or `flecs` (C, more features). The scene graph hierarchy becomes a `Parent` component with an entity ID, not a pointer."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a JavaScript event emitter implementation",
    "input": "```javascript\nclass EventEmitter {\n  constructor() {\n    this.listeners = {};\n  }\n  on(event, callback) {\n    if (!this.listeners[event]) this.listeners[event] = [];\n    this.listeners[event].push(callback);\n  }\n  emit(event, ...args) {\n    if (this.listeners[event]) {\n      this.listeners[event].forEach(cb => cb(...args));\n    }\n  }\n  off(event, callback) {\n    if (this.listeners[event]) {\n      this.listeners[event] = this.listeners[event].filter(cb => cb !== callback);\n    }\n  }\n}\n```",
    "output": "Clean basic implementation. Issues to address:\n\n1. **No `once` support** \u2014 very common need\n2. **Prototype pollution** \u2014 `emitter.on('__proto__', fn)` can cause issues since you're using a plain object\n3. **No listener limit** \u2014 easy to accidentally leak by calling `on` in a loop\n4. **Mutation during emit** \u2014 if a listener calls `off` to remove the next listener, `forEach` may still call it\n\nFixes:\n```javascript\nclass EventEmitter {\n  #listeners = new Map();\n  #maxListeners = 10;\n\n  on(event, callback) {\n    if (!this.#listeners.has(event)) this.#listeners.set(event, []);\n    const list = this.#listeners.get(event);\n    if (list.length >= this.#maxListeners) {\n      console.warn(`MaxListeners exceeded for '${event}'`);\n    }\n    list.push(callback);\n    return () => this.off(event, callback);  // Return unsubscribe function\n  }\n\n  once(event, callback) {\n    const wrapper = (...args) => {\n      this.off(event, wrapper);\n      callback(...args);\n    };\n    wrapper._original = callback;\n    this.on(event, wrapper);\n  }\n\n  emit(event, ...args) {\n    const list = this.#listeners.get(event);\n    if (!list) return;\n    [...list].forEach(cb => cb(...args));  // Copy to avoid mutation issues\n  }\n\n  off(event, callback) {\n    const list = this.#listeners.get(event);\n    if (!list) return;\n    this.#listeners.set(event, list.filter(\n      cb => cb !== callback && cb._original !== callback\n    ));\n  }\n}\n```\n\n<user>The return-unsubscribe pattern from `on` is nice. Is that common in production code?</user>\n\nYes, it's the dominant pattern in modern JS/TS. React's `useEffect` cleanup was designed around it:\n```javascript\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const unsub = emitter.on('data', handleData);\n  return unsub;  // Automatic cleanup on unmount\n}, []);\n```\n\nRxJS, MobX, Svelte stores all use it. It's superior to `off(event, callback)` because anonymous functions and closures work naturally."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a Python configuration management approach",
    "input": "Review my config setup:\n```python\nimport os\n\nDB_HOST = os.environ.get('DB_HOST', 'localhost')\nDB_PORT = int(os.environ.get('DB_PORT', '5432'))\nDB_NAME = os.environ.get('DB_NAME', 'myapp')\nDB_USER = os.environ.get('DB_USER', 'postgres')\nDB_PASSWORD = os.environ.get('DB_PASSWORD', '')\nDEBUG = os.environ.get('DEBUG', 'false').lower() == 'true'\nMAX_CONNECTIONS = int(os.environ.get('MAX_CONNECTIONS', '10'))\n```",
    "output": "Works but has problems that will bite you as the app grows:\n\n1. **No validation at startup** \u2014 `DB_PORT=abc` crashes on first DB connection, not at startup.\n2. **Scattered type coercion** \u2014 every `int()` and `.lower() == 'true'` is a bug waiting to happen.\n3. **Empty password default** \u2014 silently connects without auth if `DB_PASSWORD` is unset.\n\nUse pydantic-settings:\n```python\nfrom pydantic_settings import BaseSettings\nfrom pydantic import Field\n\nclass Settings(BaseSettings):\n    db_host: str = 'localhost'\n    db_port: int = 5432\n    db_name: str = 'myapp'\n    db_user: str = 'postgres'\n    db_password: str  # Required \u2014 no default!\n    debug: bool = False\n    max_connections: int = Field(default=10, ge=1, le=100)\n\nsettings = Settings()  # Crashes immediately if DB_PASSWORD is missing\n```\n\n<user>We're trying to keep dependencies minimal. Can I do this without pydantic?</user>\n\nYes, with a dataclass + manual validation:\n```python\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nimport os, sys\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass Settings:\n    db_host: str\n    db_port: int\n    db_password: str\n    debug: bool\n\ndef load_settings() -> Settings:\n    errors = []\n    def require(key: str) -> str:\n        val = os.environ.get(key)\n        if val is None:\n            errors.append(f\"Missing required env var: {key}\")\n            return ''\n        return val\n\n    s = Settings(\n        db_host=os.environ.get('DB_HOST', 'localhost'),\n        db_port=int(os.environ.get('DB_PORT', '5432')),\n        db_password=require('DB_PASSWORD'),\n        debug=os.environ.get('DEBUG', 'false').lower() in ('true', '1', 'yes'),\n    )\n    if errors:\n        print('\\n'.join(errors), file=sys.stderr)\n        sys.exit(1)\n    return s\n\nsettings = load_settings()\n```\n\nZero dependencies, same fail-fast behavior. The `frozen=True` dataclass prevents accidental mutation after load."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a Go middleware chain implementation",
    "input": "```go\ntype Middleware func(http.HandlerFunc) http.HandlerFunc\n\nfunc Chain(middlewares ...Middleware) Middleware {\n\treturn func(final http.HandlerFunc) http.HandlerFunc {\n\t\tfor i := len(middlewares) - 1; i >= 0; i-- {\n\t\t\tfinal = middlewares[i](final)\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn final\n\t}\n}\n```",
    "output": "The chain pattern is correct and idiomatic. A few issues:\n\n1. **Uses `http.HandlerFunc` instead of `http.Handler`** \u2014 less compatible with standard library and third-party middleware.\n2. **No response writer wrapper** \u2014 you can't capture status codes for logging without wrapping `ResponseWriter`.\n\n```go\ntype Middleware func(http.Handler) http.Handler\n\ntype statusWriter struct {\n\thttp.ResponseWriter\n\tstatus  int\n\twritten int64\n}\n\nfunc (w *statusWriter) WriteHeader(code int) {\n\tw.status = code\n\tw.ResponseWriter.WriteHeader(code)\n}\n\nfunc LoggingMiddleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {\n\treturn http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n\t\tsw := &statusWriter{ResponseWriter: w, status: 200}\n\t\tstart := time.Now()\n\t\tnext.ServeHTTP(sw, r)\n\t\tlog.Printf(\"%s %s %d %s\", r.Method, r.URL.Path, sw.status, time.Since(start))\n\t})\n}\n```\n\n<user>Why http.Handler over http.HandlerFunc? They seem interchangeable.</user>\n\n`http.Handler` is an interface, `http.HandlerFunc` is a concrete type. The difference matters for compatibility:\n\n`http.HandlerFunc`-based middleware only works with functions, not with types that implement `http.Handler` (like `http.FileServer`, `http.StripPrefix`, etc.). Using `http.Handler` costs nothing and works everywhere."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Review a Rust CLI argument parser",
    "input": "```rust\nuse std::env;\n\nfn main() {\n    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();\n    let input = if args.len() > 1 { &args[1] } else {\n        eprintln!(\"Usage: mytool <input> [--output <file>] [--verbose]\");\n        std::process::exit(1);\n    };\n    let verbose = args.contains(&\"--verbose\".to_string());\n    let output = args.iter().position(|a| a == \"--output\")\n        .map(|i| args.get(i + 1).expect(\"--output requires a value\"));\n}\n```",
    "output": "Works for a quick script but breaks in several ways:\n\n1. **Positional arg is fragile** \u2014 `mytool --verbose input.txt` fails because `args[1]` is `--verbose`.\n2. **`expect` panics** \u2014 `mytool input.txt --output` (no value) crashes unhelpfully.\n3. **No `--help`** \u2014 expected convention.\n\nFor anything beyond a one-off, use `clap`:\n```rust\nuse clap::Parser;\n\n#[derive(Parser)]\n#[command(about = \"Process input files\")]\nstruct Args {\n    /// Input file to process\n    input: String,\n    #[arg(short, long)]\n    output: Option<String>,\n    #[arg(short, long)]\n    verbose: bool,\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    let args = Args::parse();\n}\n```\n\n<user>clap adds a lot to compile time. Is there something lighter?</user>\n\nTwo good options:\n\n**`lexopt`** \u2014 minimal, no macros, ~10KB:\n```rust\nuse lexopt::prelude::*;\n\nfn main() -> Result<(), lexopt::Error> {\n    let mut parser = lexopt::Parser::from_env();\n    let mut input = None;\n    let mut output = None;\n    let mut verbose = false;\n\n    while let Some(arg) = parser.next()? {\n        match arg {\n            Short('o') | Long(\"output\") => output = Some(parser.value()?.parse()?),\n            Short('v') | Long(\"verbose\") => verbose = true,\n            Value(val) if input.is_none() => input = Some(val.parse()?),\n            _ => return Err(arg.unexpected()),\n        }\n    }\n    Ok(())\n}\n```\n\n**`pico-args`** \u2014 even simpler. For simple CLIs, either of these is perfectly fine."
})

