pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a rate limiter for a multi-tenant API",
    "input": "I need to add rate limiting to our API. We have ~500 tenants, each with different rate limit tiers (free: 100 req/min, pro: 1000, enterprise: 10000). Running 4 API instances behind a load balancer.",
    "output": "Key question: do you need per-tenant limits enforced globally across all 4 instances, or is per-instance limiting acceptable?\n\n<user>Needs to be global \u2014 some tenants have been abusing by distributing requests across instances.</user>\n\nThen you need a shared state store. Standard approach is Redis with a sliding window counter:\n\n```python\nclass RateLimiter:\n    def __init__(self, redis_client: redis.Redis):\n        self.redis = redis_client\n    \n    def is_allowed(self, tenant_id: str, limit: int, window_seconds: int = 60) -> bool:\n        key = f\"ratelimit:{tenant_id}\"\n        now = time.time()\n        pipe = self.redis.pipeline()\n        pipe.zremrangebyscore(key, 0, now - window_seconds)\n        pipe.zadd(key, {f\"{now}:{id(object())}\": now})\n        pipe.zcard(key)\n        pipe.expire(key, window_seconds)\n        _, _, count, _ = pipe.execute()\n        return count <= limit\n```\n\nThis uses a Redis sorted set for a true sliding window.\n\n<user>What about latency? Adding a Redis call to every request seems expensive.</user>\n\nThe pipeline call adds ~0.5ms per request (4 commands in 1 round trip). For 500 tenants at your scale, this is fine. If you need lower latency, keep an approximate counter locally and sync to Redis periodically. But for most cases, the pipeline approach is sufficient.\n\n<user>How do we handle the rate limit response?</user>\n\nReturn 429 immediately with retry headers:\n```python\nif not limiter.is_allowed(tenant_id, limit):\n    resp = jsonify({\"error\": \"rate limit exceeded\"})\n    resp.status_code = 429\n    resp.headers[\"Retry-After\"] = str(int(window_remaining))\n    resp.headers[\"X-RateLimit-Limit\"] = str(limit)\n    resp.headers[\"X-RateLimit-Remaining\"] = str(max(0, limit - count))\n    return resp\n```\n\nNever queue \u2014 it turns a rate limiter into an unbounded work queue. Include `X-RateLimit-*` headers on EVERY response so well-behaved clients can self-throttle."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a plugin system for a Python application",
    "input": "I want to add a plugin system to my data processing tool. Users should be able to write custom transformers that plug into the pipeline.",
    "output": "What's the deployment model? Are plugins installed as pip packages, dropped as .py files into a directory, or configured via YAML?\n\n<user>Pip packages for now, but eventually we want drop-in .py files too. They shouldn't crash the host.</user>\n\nUse Python's `entry_points` for pip-installed plugins and dynamic import for drop-ins:\n\n```python\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\nimport importlib.metadata\n\nclass TransformerPlugin(ABC):\n    name: str = \"unnamed\"\n    \n    @abstractmethod\n    def transform(self, data: dict) -> dict:\n        ...\n\nclass PluginRegistry:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._plugins: dict[str, TransformerPlugin] = {}\n    \n    def discover_entrypoints(self, group: str = \"myapp.plugins\"):\n        for ep in importlib.metadata.entry_points(group=group):\n            try:\n                cls = ep.load()\n                plugin = cls()\n                self._plugins[plugin.name] = plugin\n            except Exception as e:\n                logger.warning(f\"Failed to load plugin {ep.name}: {e}\")\n    \n    def run_all(self, data: dict) -> dict:\n        for name, plugin in self._plugins.items():\n            try:\n                data = plugin.transform(data)\n            except Exception as e:\n                logger.error(f\"Plugin '{name}' failed: {e}\")\n        return data\n```\n\n<user>How would a user write a plugin as a pip package?</user>\n\nA minimal plugin package:\n```python\n# my_plugin.py\nfrom myapp.plugins import TransformerPlugin\n\nclass UpperCasePlugin(TransformerPlugin):\n    name = \"uppercase\"\n    def transform(self, data: dict) -> dict:\n        data[\"text\"] = data[\"text\"].upper()\n        return data\n```\n\n```toml\n# pyproject.toml\n[project.entry-points.\"myapp.plugins\"]\nuppercase = \"my_plugin:UpperCasePlugin\"\n```\n\n`pip install .` and the plugin is automatically discovered.\n\n<user>What about sandboxing? If a plugin does `import os; os.remove('/')` we're in trouble.</user>\n\nTrue sandboxing in Python is hard. Best practical option: run each plugin in a subprocess with timeout and resource limits:\n```python\ndef run_sandboxed(plugin_path: str, data: dict, timeout: int = 30) -> dict:\n    result = subprocess.run(\n        [sys.executable, \"-c\", \"...\"],\n        input=json.dumps(data), capture_output=True, timeout=timeout\n    )\n    return json.loads(result.stdout)\n```\n\nPlugins can't affect the host process. For maximum isolation, use WASM via `wasmtime-py`. For most cases, subprocess with timeout is the sweet spot."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a caching strategy for a read-heavy API",
    "input": "Our API serves product data. 95% reads, 5% writes. Getting 10k req/sec, DB is struggling. Need a caching strategy.",
    "output": "What's the data freshness requirement? Can users see stale data for a few seconds, or does a price change need to reflect immediately?\n\n<user>Product details can be stale for 5 minutes. Prices and inventory must be fresh within 10 seconds.</user>\n\nDifferent TTLs for different data types. Two-tier strategy:\n\n**Tier 1: In-process cache** \u2014 product details with 5-min TTL, eliminates network hop.\n**Tier 2: Redis** \u2014 prices/inventory with 10-second TTL, shared across instances.\n\n```python\nfrom cachetools import TTLCache\n\ndetails_cache = TTLCache(maxsize=10_000, ttl=300)\n\ndef get_product(product_id: str) -> dict:\n    if product_id in details_cache:\n        details = details_cache[product_id]\n    else:\n        cached = redis_client.get(f\"product:{product_id}\")\n        if cached:\n            details = json.loads(cached)\n        else:\n            details = db.get_product(product_id)\n            redis_client.setex(f\"product:{product_id}\", 300, json.dumps(details))\n        details_cache[product_id] = details\n    \n    price = get_price(product_id)  # 10s TTL in Redis\n    return {**details, \"price\": price}\n```\n\n<user>What about cache invalidation on writes?</user>\n\nWrite-through invalidation with pub/sub for multi-instance:\n```python\ndef update_product(product_id: str, updates: dict):\n    db.update_product(product_id, updates)\n    redis_client.delete(f\"product:{product_id}\")\n    details_cache.pop(product_id, None)\n    redis_client.publish(\"cache_invalidation\", product_id)\n```\n\nEach instance subscribes and clears its local cache when notified. Sub-second invalidation across all instances.\n\n<user>What about thundering herd when 1000 requests hit a cache miss simultaneously?</user>\n\nUse singleflight pattern \u2014 serialize cache population with a lock:\n```python\n_locks = defaultdict(threading.Lock)\n\ndef get_with_singleflight(product_id: str) -> dict:\n    cached = redis_client.get(f\"product:{product_id}\")\n    if cached:\n        return json.loads(cached)\n    with _locks[product_id]:\n        cached = redis_client.get(f\"product:{product_id}\")  # Double-check\n        if cached:\n            return json.loads(cached)\n        data = db.get_product(product_id)\n        redis_client.setex(f\"product:{product_id}\", 300, json.dumps(data))\n        return data\n```\n\nOnly one request reaches the DB. For cross-instance, use a Redis lock (`SET key NX EX 5`)."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design an event-driven architecture for order processing",
    "input": "We're building an e-commerce backend. Currently everything is synchronous: place order, charge payment, update inventory, send email, return response. Response times are 3-5 seconds.",
    "output": "The synchronous chain is the bottleneck. Which steps must complete before the user gets a response?\n\n<user>Payment must succeed. Inventory can be eventually consistent. Email can be delayed.</user>\n\nArchitecture:\n\n**Synchronous (in the request):** Validate order, authorize payment, return 202 Accepted.\n**Asynchronous (via event queue):** Capture payment, update inventory, send email.\n\nResponse time drops from 3-5s to ~500ms.\n\n```python\n# views.py\ndef create_order(request):\n    order = Order.objects.create(...)\n    intent = stripe.PaymentIntent.create(amount=order.total, confirm=True)\n    order.payment_intent_id = intent.id\n    order.save()\n    capture_payment.delay(order.id)  # Async\n    return JsonResponse({'order_id': order.id, 'status': 'processing'}, status=202)\n\n# tasks.py\n@shared_task(bind=True, max_retries=3, default_retry_delay=60)\ndef capture_payment(self, order_id):\n    try:\n        order = Order.objects.get(id=order_id)\n        stripe.PaymentIntent.capture(order.payment_intent_id)\n        order.status = 'paid'\n        order.save()\n        update_inventory.delay(order_id)\n        send_confirmation_email.delay(order_id)\n    except stripe.error.StripeError as e:\n        self.retry(exc=e)\n```\n\n<user>What message queue should we use? We're a Python/Django shop.</user>\n\nCelery + Redis. You already have Redis for caching probably. Celery handles retries, dead-letter queues, and monitoring (Flower dashboard) out of the box.\n\n<user>What happens if payment capture fails after 3 retries?</user>\n\nDead-letter queue + alerting:\n```python\nif self.request.retries >= self.max_retries:\n    order.status = 'payment_failed'\n    order.save()\n    alert_ops_team.delay(order_id, str(e))\n    return\n```\n\nSend a notification to the user with a link to retry. Never silently fail on payments."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a database migration strategy for zero-downtime deployments",
    "input": "We deploy 5-10 times a day. Sometimes migrations lock tables and cause 30-second downtimes. PostgreSQL 14 with Django.",
    "output": "The main locking culprits in PostgreSQL migrations:\n1. `ADD COLUMN ... NOT NULL` (full table scan)\n2. `CREATE INDEX` (locks writes)\n3. `ALTER COLUMN TYPE` (full table rewrite)\n\nWhich of these are you running? How big are your tables?\n\n<user>Largest table is 50M rows. We frequently add NOT NULL columns and create indexes.</user>\n\n**Adding NOT NULL column \u2014 two-step deploy:**\n```python\n# Migration 1: Add nullable column\noperations = [\n    migrations.AddField(model_name='order', name='tracking_id',\n        field=models.CharField(max_length=100, null=True, default='')),\n]\n\n# Backfill data, then...\n\n# Migration 2: Add NOT NULL constraint\noperations = [\n    migrations.AlterField(model_name='order', name='tracking_id',\n        field=models.CharField(max_length=100, default='')),\n]\n```\n\n**Creating indexes \u2014 CONCURRENTLY:**\n```python\nclass Migration(migrations.Migration):\n    atomic = False  # Required for CONCURRENTLY\n    operations = [\n        migrations.RunSQL(\n            \"CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_order_tracking ON orders_order(tracking_id);\",\n            reverse_sql=\"DROP INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_order_tracking;\",\n        ),\n    ]\n```\n\n<user>What about column renames? We saw 45 seconds of locking.</user>\n\nColumn renames are actually instant in PostgreSQL (catalog update only). The 45 seconds was likely the migration waiting for a long-running query to release its lock.\n\nFix: set a lock timeout:\n```python\noperations = [\n    migrations.RunSQL(\"SET lock_timeout = '5s';\"),\n    migrations.RenameField(model_name='order', old_name='old_col', new_name='new_col'),\n    migrations.RunSQL(\"SET lock_timeout = DEFAULT;\"),\n]\n```\n\nIf the lock can't be acquired in 5s, the migration fails instead of blocking all queries. Retry during low traffic. Also install `django-pg-zero-downtime-migrations` for automatic safety."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a file upload pipeline for large files",
    "input": "Users need to upload files up to 5GB. Currently we accept the whole file in the API request then store in S3. Large uploads time out.",
    "output": "What client types? Browser, mobile, CLI? And do you need post-processing (virus scan, metadata extraction)?\n\n<user>Mostly browser. Need virus scan and metadata extraction after upload.</user>\n\nUse **presigned URL direct upload** to bypass your server:\n\n```\nBrowser -> API: \"I want to upload report.pdf (2GB)\"\nAPI -> S3: Generate presigned PUT URL\nAPI -> Browser: Here's the presigned URL + upload ID\nBrowser -> S3: Direct upload with progress\nBrowser -> API: \"Upload complete\"\nAPI -> Queue: Start processing\n```\n\n```python\n@app.post(\"/uploads/initiate\")\ndef initiate_upload(filename: str, content_type: str, size: int):\n    upload_id = str(uuid4())\n    key = f\"uploads/{upload_id}/{filename}\"\n    presigned = s3.generate_presigned_url(\n        'put_object',\n        Params={'Bucket': 'my-bucket', 'Key': key, 'ContentType': content_type},\n        ExpiresIn=3600\n    )\n    db.save_upload(upload_id, filename=filename, status='pending', key=key)\n    return {'upload_id': upload_id, 'presigned_url': presigned}\n```\n\n<user>What about resumable uploads? 5GB upload failing at 4GB is unacceptable.</user>\n\nUse S3 multipart upload. Browser uploads in chunks, failed chunks retry independently:\n\n```python\n@app.post(\"/uploads/initiate-multipart\")\ndef initiate_multipart(filename: str, size: int):\n    mpu = s3.create_multipart_upload(Bucket='my-bucket', Key=key)\n    chunk_size = 100 * 1024 * 1024  # 100MB\n    num_parts = math.ceil(size / chunk_size)\n    presigned_urls = [\n        {'part_number': i, 'url': s3.generate_presigned_url(\n            'upload_part',\n            Params={'Bucket': 'my-bucket', 'Key': key,\n                    'UploadId': mpu['UploadId'], 'PartNumber': i},\n            ExpiresIn=3600\n        )} for i in range(1, num_parts + 1)\n    ]\n    return {'upload_id': mpu['UploadId'], 'parts': presigned_urls}\n```\n\n<user>Can we use tus protocol instead?</user>\n\nYes. Use `tusd` as a sidecar:\n```yaml\ntusd:\n  image: tusproject/tusd\n  command: -s3-bucket my-bucket -hooks-http http://api:8000/hooks/tus\n```\n\nThe browser uses `tus-js-client`, tusd handles chunking/resumption/S3 storage, your API gets webhook notifications. Zero upload code to maintain. Best approach if you don't need custom upload logic."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a notification system with multiple delivery channels",
    "input": "Need notifications via email, push, SMS, and in-app. Users configure which channels they want per notification type.",
    "output": "What's the volume and delivery guarantee? Financial alerts vs marketing?\n\n<user>Mix. Transaction alerts must be guaranteed (email + in-app minimum). Marketing is best-effort. ~100k notifications/day.</user>\n\nClean channel abstraction:\n\n```python\nclass Channel(Enum):\n    EMAIL = \"email\"\n    PUSH = \"push\"\n    SMS = \"sms\"\n    IN_APP = \"in_app\"\n\nclass Priority(Enum):\n    CRITICAL = \"critical\"  # Retry until delivered\n    NORMAL = \"normal\"      # Retry 3x\n    LOW = \"low\"            # Best effort\n\n@dataclass\nclass Notification:\n    user_id: str\n    type: str\n    title: str\n    body: str\n    priority: Priority = Priority.NORMAL\n\nclass NotificationService:\n    def send(self, notification: Notification):\n        channels = self.get_user_channels(notification.user_id, notification.type)\n        for channel in channels:\n            send_notification_task.delay(channel=channel, notification=asdict(notification))\n```\n\n<user>How do we handle user preferences? Some want email for everything, others only push for marketing.</user>\n\nPreference matrix of (user, notification_type, channel):\n\n```python\nclass PreferenceService:\n    DEFAULTS = {\n        'order_confirmed': {Channel.EMAIL: True, Channel.IN_APP: True},\n        'marketing': {Channel.EMAIL: True, Channel.PUSH: False},\n    }\n    NON_OPTIONAL = {'password_reset', 'account_security'}  # Can't disable\n    \n    def get_channels(self, user_id: str, notification_type: str) -> list[Channel]:\n        if notification_type in self.NON_OPTIONAL:\n            return list(self.DEFAULTS[notification_type].keys())\n        defaults = self.DEFAULTS.get(notification_type, {})\n        overrides = db.get_preferences(user_id, notification_type)\n        return [ch for ch, default in defaults.items()\n                if overrides.get(ch, default)]\n```\n\n<user>For guaranteed delivery on critical notifications, what retry strategy?</user>\n\nEscalating retry with channel fallback: try push first (fastest), then SMS, then email. If all fail, exponential backoff up to 10 retries (~17 hours). After exhausting retries, alert ops. Always store in-app notifications in the database regardless of delivery \u2014 they serve as audit trail and fallback."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a search architecture for a content platform",
    "input": "We have 2M articles. Currently using PostgreSQL full-text search but it's slow (2-3 seconds) and results aren't great. Should we switch to Elasticsearch?",
    "output": "Before recommending Elasticsearch \u2014 what specifically is bad about the results? Slow queries can be fixed with proper indexes. What does \"not great\" mean?\n\n<user>Ranking is poor \u2014 searching \"python async\" returns articles about snakes above programming articles. No typo tolerance. We also want faceted search.</user>\n\nThose are legitimate reasons to move beyond PostgreSQL FTS. But Elasticsearch might be overkill for 2M docs. Consider:\n\n1. **Meilisearch** \u2014 typo-tolerant, great relevance out of the box, facets, easy to run. Best for your scale.\n2. **Elasticsearch** \u2014 powerful but complex to operate. Worth it at 100M+ docs.\n3. **Typesense** \u2014 similar to Meilisearch.\n\nFor 2M articles, Meilisearch is my recommendation:\n```python\nclient = meilisearch.Client('http://localhost:7700', 'master-key')\nindex = client.index('articles')\nindex.update_settings({\n    'searchableAttributes': ['title', 'body', 'tags'],\n    'filterableAttributes': ['category', 'author', 'published_date'],\n    'rankingRules': ['words', 'typo', 'proximity', 'attribute', 'sort', 'exactness']\n})\n```\n\n<user>How do we keep the search index in sync with PostgreSQL?</user>\n\nApplication-level sync is simplest:\n```python\nclass Article(models.Model):\n    def save(self, **kwargs):\n        super().save(**kwargs)\n        update_search_index.delay(self.id)\n```\n\nPlus a periodic full reindex as a safety net. Use CDC (Change Data Capture) only if you need zero-lag sync.\n\n<user>What about hybrid search \u2014 combining keyword with semantic/vector search?</user>\n\nMeilisearch 1.3+ has built-in hybrid search:\n```python\nindex.update_settings({\n    'embedders': {\n        'default': {\n            'source': 'huggingFace',\n            'model': 'BAAI/bge-small-en-v1.5'\n        }\n    }\n})\nresults = index.search('how to handle async errors', {\n    'hybrid': {'semanticRatio': 0.5}\n})\n```\n\nThis catches queries where exact words don't appear but meaning matches. At 2M docs, embedding everything takes about 2 hours on a GPU."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a background job system for a small team",
    "input": "We need background jobs (emails, reports, data imports). Currently cron + Python scripts. No retries, no monitoring, no history.",
    "output": "What's your infrastructure? Redis available? And what framework?\n\n<user>Flask app, Redis for sessions. Team of 3 developers. Want simple, not Kubernetes-level orchestration.</user>\n\nFor Flask with Redis, **RQ (Redis Queue)** is the sweet spot \u2014 much simpler than Celery:\n\n```python\nfrom rq import Queue, Retry\n\nqueue = Queue(connection=redis_conn)\nhigh = Queue('high', connection=redis_conn)\n\n# Enqueue with retry\nqueue.enqueue(send_welcome_email, user.id, retry=Retry(max=3, interval=[60, 300, 900]))\n\n# High priority\nhigh.enqueue(send_password_reset, user.id)\n\n# Delayed\nqueue.enqueue_in(timedelta(hours=24), send_followup, user.id)\n```\n\nRun workers: `rq worker high default --with-scheduler`\n\n<user>What about monitoring failed jobs?</user>\n\nUse `rq-dashboard`:\n```bash\npip install rq-dashboard\nrq-dashboard  # Web UI on port 9181\n```\n\nShows queues, workers, failed jobs, lets you retry/delete from the UI.\n\n<user>When would we outgrow RQ and need Celery?</user>\n\nRQ limitations that push to Celery:\n\n1. **No task chaining/workflows** \u2014 Celery has `chain`, `chord`, `group`\n2. **Single broker** \u2014 RQ only works with Redis; Celery supports RabbitMQ, SQS\n3. **No rate limiting** \u2014 Celery has built-in `rate_limit='10/m'`\n4. **No periodic tasks** \u2014 RQ-scheduler exists but less mature than Celery Beat\n\nAt your scale (3 devs, Flask, Redis), RQ will serve you well for 1-2 years."
})

pairs.append({
    "instruction": "Design a feature flag system",
    "input": "We want to roll out features gradually \u2014 internal users first, then 10%, 50%, 100%. What's a good approach?",
    "output": "Build it or use a service? And what targeting do you need beyond percentages?\n\n<user>Build it. Need percentage rollout, user ID targeting (beta testers), and plan-based targeting (pro users first).</user>\n\nClean implementation:\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass FeatureFlag:\n    name: str\n    enabled: bool = False\n    percentage: int = 0\n    user_ids: set[str] = field(default_factory=set)\n    plans: set[str] = field(default_factory=set)\n    \n    def is_enabled_for(self, user_id: str, plan: str = 'free') -> bool:\n        if not self.enabled:\n            return False\n        if user_id in self.user_ids:\n            return True\n        if self.plans and plan in self.plans:\n            return True\n        if self.percentage > 0:\n            hash_val = int(hashlib.md5(f\"{self.name}:{user_id}\".encode()).hexdigest()[:8], 16)\n            return (hash_val % 100) < self.percentage\n        return False\n```\n\nThe MD5 hash ensures consistent assignment \u2014 same user always gets the same result.\n\n<user>How do we manage the flags? Admin UI? Config file?</user>\n\nStore in Redis (fast reads) with a simple admin API:\n```python\n@app.post('/admin/flags')\ndef create_flag():\n    flag = FeatureFlag(**request.json)\n    redis_client.set(f\"flag:{flag.name}\", json.dumps(asdict(flag)))\n    audit_log.info(f\"Flag '{flag.name}' created by {current_user.id}\")\n    return jsonify({'created': flag.name})\n```\n\nUsage:\n```python\nif flags.check('new_dashboard', current_user.id, current_user.plan):\n    return render_template('dashboard_v2.html')\nreturn render_template('dashboard.html')\n```\n\nKeep an audit log of every change \u2014 you'll need it when debugging \"why did this user see the new feature?\""
})

